div.div: The following operations update or push a dummy at the head.
The operations, and why they need a dummy to exist at the head:

ul.li: We want to store hold_count on dummies only, so that F+C is not prevented from replacing nodes holding persisted data.
Performance. Prevent O(n) re-traversal from the head, when eventually ready to replace or insert. (For details, see the separate doc diagram on concurrent LL modification.)

div.div: The operations, and how they modify the head end:

li.span: If a dummy exists, modify its hold_count as += 1.

ul.li: If pushing, initialize node w/ hold_count = 1.
If a dummy exists, do not modify it.
If pushing, initialize node w/ hold_count = 0.

div.div:
Consequences of doing these opers non-atomically:
By the time a txn thread holds snap_commit_ver_hi_incl=x, the boundary between (x <--> x+1) might already have been erased.
Hence, conflict-checking yields false-conflicts at a higher probability, than if we read and held atomically. If done non-atomically, conflict-checking is guaranteed not to over-check (i.e. encroach into x and lower versions) iff there are zero concurrent commitments --- this defeats the main advantage of SSI wrt serial execution.
Possible enforcement of correctness:
It doesn't affect the correctness of the conflict-checking algo. When a conflict is found, we retry the transaction.
Should the group be atomic?:
Yes.

Consequences of doing these opers non-atomically:
By the time a thread holds list_ver=x, x might already have been erased.
The "gobally minimum held list ver" can jump backwards.
Possible enforcement of correctness:
Each traversing thread must first hold a list_ver and make this holding information available to the garbage collector; and then traverse. To inform this and then wait for confirmation requires synchronization.
Should the group be atomic?:
Yes.

div.div:

Other txns (not the txn that's committing) behave as follows:
Txn sees P=x, and defines its initial snapshot as ( -inf ~ x ].
It traverses over but ignores the node with commit_ver=x+1.
Txn sees P = x' > x; and changes its snapshot to [ x+1 ~ x' ].
This time it does not ignore the node with commit_ver=x+1.
Feasibly correct, but awkward.

ol.li:
Txn sees P=x+1, and defines its initial snapshot as ( -inf ~ x+1 ].
But it does not traverse over a node with commit_ver=x+1.

If the txn is not read-only, it must eventually read commit_ver=x+1.
To do so, it must wait until nodes with commit_ver>=x+1 are pushed.
Meanwhile, it must not unhold the snapshot's list_ver; or else the commit_ver boundary (x <--> x+1) might disappear.

Txn refreshes P and sees P=x' > x+1.
It migt have to repeat the above indefinitely.

Traversing threads (eg txns) behave as follows:
Txn sees P=x, and holds list_ver=x as non-GC'able.
It actually never traverses over nodes which became dangling as of list_ver=x+1, but nevertheless prevents these nodes from being GC'd.
Txn un-holds list_ver=x.
Now those said nodes can be GC'd. There is delay, but no incorrectness.
Correct.

Traversing threads (eg txns) behave as follows:
Txn sees P=x+1, and holds list_ver=x+1 as being in use.
Meanwhile, it traverses over list version x, over nodes that will become dangling as of list_ver=x+1.
F+C replaces a slice, leaving the traversable list in version x+1.
Garbage collector deletes dangling nodes that became dangling as of list_ver=x+1.
Txn may be still reading them! Use-after-free!
Incorrect!
